<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="272" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,292,1651]" pageId="1" pageNumber="272">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,322,1263,1290]" pageId="1" pageNumber="272">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
This new genus is similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Dworakowska, 1993" authorityName="Dworakowska" authorityYear="1993" box="[671,1001,1264,1291]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Cuanta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="272" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[671,753,1265,1291]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="272">Cuanta</emphasis>
Dworakowska, 1993
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Dworakowska, 1972" authorityName="Dworakowska" authorityYear="1972" box="[1015,1432,1264,1290]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Michalowskiya" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="272" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1015,1185,1264,1290]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="272">Michalowskiya</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Dworakowska, I." box="[1194,1432,1264,1290]" pageId="1" pageNumber="272" pagination="117 - 125" refId="ref3441" refString="Dworakowska, I. (1972) On some Oriental genera of Typhlocybinae (Auchenorrhyncha, Cicadellidae). Bulletin de l'Academie Polonaise des Sciences, II, 20 (2), 117 - 125." type="journal article" year="1972">Dworakowska, 1972</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Matsumura, 1931" authorityName="Matsumura" authorityYear="1931" box="[151,475,1300,1327]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Naratettix" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="272" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,265,1301,1326]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="272">Naratettix</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Matsumura, S." box="[273,475,1300,1327]" pageId="1" pageNumber="272" pagination="55 - 91" refId="ref3677" refString="Matsumura, S. (1931) A revision of the Palaearctic and Oriental typhlocybid-genera with descriptions of new species and new genera. Insecta Matsumurana, 6 (1 - 2), 55 - 91, pls. II-III." type="journal article" year="1931">Matsumura, 1931</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, etc, in the flattened body and the relative length of pronotum to mesonotum. In the features of the fore wing venation, this genus closely resembles 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Matsumura" authorityYear="1931" box="[869,983,1337,1362]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Naratettix" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="272" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[869,983,1337,1362]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="272">Naratettix</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but differs in having the 2nd apical cell shorter and with the base distinctly narrowed but not stalked, and the vein MP”+CuA’ reaching the wing apex. The features of the male style show similarity to those of 
<taxonomicName authority="Dworakowska, 1993" authorityName="Dworakowska" authorityYear="1993" box="[736,1067,1408,1434]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Platfusa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="272" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[736,829,1408,1434]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="272">Platfusa</emphasis>
Dworakowska, 1993
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Thapa, 1989" authorityName="Thapa" authorityYear="1989" box="[1119,1390,1408,1434]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Takagioma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="272" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1119,1242,1408,1434]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="272">Takagioma</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Thapa, V. K." box="[1248,1390,1408,1434]" pageId="1" pageNumber="272" pagination="111 - 122" refId="ref3791" refString="Thapa, V. K. (1989) Some more new typhlocybine leafhoppers (Homoptera, Cicadellidae) from the Kathmandu area, Nepal. Insecta Matsumurana, New Series, 42, 111 - 122." type="journal article" year="1989">Thapa, 1989</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
. Although the presence of a long aedeagal preatrium (
<figureCitation box="[720,802,1444,1470]" captionStart="FIGURES 18–26" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1895,1920]" captionTargetBox="[156,1432,285,1865]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,273,1876]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 18–26. Stictotettix cleyerae sp. nov. Male abdominal sternal apodemes (18), ♀ 7th abdominal sternite (19) and ♂ genitalia (20–26).—20, Genital capsule in lateral view; 21, pygofer in dorsal view; 22, subgenital plate in ventral view; 23, style and connective in dorsal view; 24, aedeagus in lateral view; 25, 26, aedeagal apex in caudal (25) and dorsal (26) views. Scales: 0.05 mm (25, 26), 0.1 mm (23, 24), 0.2 mm (18–22)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3269132/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="272">Fig. 24</figureCitation>
) is common to 
<taxonomicName authority="Anufriev, 1970" authorityName="Anufriev" authorityYear="1970" box="[978,1330,1444,1470]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Emelyanoviana" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="272" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[978,1152,1444,1470]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="272">Emelyanoviana</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Anufriev, G. A." box="[1157,1330,1444,1470]" pageId="1" pageNumber="272" pagination="261 - 263" refId="ref3246" refString="Anufriev, G. A. (1970) New genera of Palearctic Dikraneurini (Homoptera, Cicadellidae, Typhlocybinae). Bulletin de l'Academie Polonaise des Sciences, II, 18 (5), 261 - 263." type="journal article" year="1970">Anufriev, 1970</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Fieber, 1866" authorityName="Fieber" authorityYear="1866" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Erythria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="272" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1341,1436,1444,1470]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="272">Erythria</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Fieber, F. X." box="[151,290,1480,1506]" pageId="1" pageNumber="272" pagination="497 - 516" refId="ref3595" refString="Fieber, F. X. (1866) Neue Gattungen und Arten in Homoptern (Cicadina Bur.). Verhandlungen der Kaiserlich-Koniglichen Zoologisch-botanischen Gesellschaft Wien, 16, 497 - 516. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 9291" type="journal article" year="1866">Fieber, 1866</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Matsumura, 1932" authorityName="Matsumura" authorityYear="1932" box="[342,641,1480,1507]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Igutettix" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="272" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[342,435,1481,1506]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="272">Igutettix</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Matsumura, S." box="[442,641,1480,1507]" pageId="1" pageNumber="272" pagination="93 - 120" refId="ref3719" refString="Matsumura, S. (1932) A revision of the Palaearctic and Oriental typhlocybid-genera with descriptions of new species and new genera. Insecta Matsumurana, 6 (3), 93 - 120." type="journal article" year="1932">Matsumura, 1932</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, the new genus is characterized by the features of the aedeagus, with the atrium extremely developed and the shaft invaginated into the atrium basally. Therefore, the aedeagal atrium is produced dorsocaudally and surrounds the base of shaft (
<figureCitation box="[752,890,1552,1579]" captionStart="FIGURES 18–26" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1895,1920]" captionTargetBox="[156,1432,285,1865]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,273,1876]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 18–26. Stictotettix cleyerae sp. nov. Male abdominal sternal apodemes (18), ♀ 7th abdominal sternite (19) and ♂ genitalia (20–26).—20, Genital capsule in lateral view; 21, pygofer in dorsal view; 22, subgenital plate in ventral view; 23, style and connective in dorsal view; 24, aedeagus in lateral view; 25, 26, aedeagal apex in caudal (25) and dorsal (26) views. Scales: 0.05 mm (25, 26), 0.1 mm (23, 24), 0.2 mm (18–22)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3269132/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="272">Figs. 24–26</figureCitation>
). These are unique among dikraneurine genera.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="272" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,292,1651]" pageId="1" pageNumber="272">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1588,1614]" pageId="1" pageNumber="272">Etymology.</emphasis>
This genus is masculine in gender and it is derived from two Greek words: stictos (marked, spotted) + tettix (cicada).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
